Here I'm going to talk all about functions in JS! 


https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joKEi4RR9-o


Function Declarations - Hoisted to top. So If I try to use the function before the function implementation it won't throw an error. 

```
    function sayHello() {
        console.log("Hello!")
    }
```


Function Expressions - are not hoisted. They are written a bit differently like this: 

```
    const sayHello = function() {
        console.log("Hello!")
    }
```

This can be use const/let/var, but does not matter. Here we can see that we are adding a variable with the value of a function essentially. For example, what we can do is this: 

```
    function someFunction(sayHello) {
        console.log("I'm a normal function")
        sayHello();
    }
```

What we have here is a function, which has an argument which is a function and we execute both. 
Also we can, instead of writing these functions directly in the parameter. 


Imidiatelly invoked function expression

```
    const sayHello = (function(){
        console.log("Hello!")
    })()
```

reson to use - Encapsulation.. No one can access a IIFE.. Easily to write about

